2. Supplemental terms — attribution, citation, and process
----------------------------------------------------------

These terms apply in addition to Section 1. They are intended to ensure fair credit for the
project while keeping the Software **free to use** for most purposes, including **commercial use**,
subject to the rules below.

2.1 Redistribution of the Software
    Whenever you **redistribute** the Software in source or binary form (for example, in a
    repository, package, or container image that includes a substantial part of this codebase),
    you must:
    (a) Keep intact the **copyright notice**, this **entire LICENSE file** (Sections 1 and 2), and
        **NOTICE** (or equivalent project attribution file) in your distribution; and
    (b) Not remove or misrepresent the origin of the Software.

2.2 Acknowledgment and citation (public, research, and documented products)
    If you do **any** of the following, you must provide a **citation or acknowledgment** that
    meets the **preferred format** in **CITATION.cff** (or the “License and citation” / “How to cite”
    section in the project **README** if **CITATION.cff** is unavailable), including at minimum the
    **project name** (MCP Test Harness), **author** (as listed in **CITATION.cff** or **NOTICE**),
    **source URL** of this project, and **year or version** when applicable:

    (a) **Academic, research, or technical publication** (paper, preprint, thesis, report) that
        describes or evaluates work that **materially** uses or builds on the Software;
    (b) **Publicly distributed** software, services, or products whose **end-user or developer
        documentation** (including README, help pages, or release notes) describes a feature
        that **substantially** relies on the Software, unless that documentation is limited to
        “internal” packages not offered to the public; or
    (c) **Public training, courses, or similar materials** (including slides or videos offered to
        third parties) that **teach** or **demonstrate** this Software or a derivative in a
        **substantive** way.

2.3 Private and internal use
    **Solely private** or **internal** use (e.g. running tests in your private CI, without
    redistributing the Software or **publicly** claiming a product that depends on it in a way
    covered by 2.2) does not require a separate public citation, provided you still comply with
    Section 1 and 2.1 for any **redistribution** you perform.

2.4 Process (how to comply in practice)
    (1) **Publications and formal reports:** Cite the Software using the **metadata and suggested
        wording** in **CITATION.cff** (BibTeX, APA, or similar block as provided or adapted there);
        include the **repository URL** and, when applicable, a **version or commit** and **date
        accessed**.
    (2) **Repositories and forks:** Keep a copy of this **LICENSE**, **NOTICE**, and
        **CITATION.cff** (or a short “see upstream LICENSE” link that preserves the same
        obligations) in your tree when you **redistribute** a substantial part of the Software.
    (3) **Products and services:** In **public** documentation, credits, or “About” pages,
        add a one-line **acknowledgment** per **CITATION.cff** / README.
    (4) **Unknown format:** If your venue does not have a @software type, use a **@misc** or
        **acknowledgment paragraph** with the same bibliographic data as in **CITATION.cff**.

2.5 No additional patent grant; no trademark
    Nothing in this file grants any trademark or patent rights. You must not use the author’s
    or project’s names to imply endorsement without permission, except to **attribute** the
    Software as required above.

2.6 Severability
    If any part of Section 2 is held unenforceable, the remaining terms, including Section 1,
    remain in effect to the maximum extent permitted by law.
